579. Geriatrics. 2001 Jan;56(1):35-9; quiz 40.

Successful aging. How increased life expectancy and medical advances are 
changing geriatric care.

Cassel CK(1).

Author information:
(1)Henry L. Schwartz Department of Geriatrics and Adult Development, Mount Sinai 
School of Medicine, New York, NY, USA.

If the unprecedented increase in life expectancy has a downside, it is the 
exposure of risk to chronic age-related disorders. As clinicians work to foster 
healthy aging, we must also seek ways to prevent the disabling disorders that 
keep many older persons from enjoying their longevity. The high prevalence of 
chronic illness and functional limitation among older persons underscores the 
need for strategically directed health and social services. Successful patient 
management must extend beyond diagnosis and disease treatment and include 
promotion of function and prevention of decline. Achieving this goal requires a 
seamless continuum of management and interdisciplinary caregiving. There also 
must be a focus on improving the understanding of the science of aging. New 
treatment approaches for managing aging may one day include cognitive enhancers, 
designer hormones, telomerase, antioxidants, and gene therapy.

